PE Women Details: 12 HELLP
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Mild preeclampsia, defined as mild hypertension plus proteinuriam, severe preeclampsia, or HELLP
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Inclusion : women who had undergone >=2 term pregnancies unaffected by preeclampsia  Exclusion :  family history of preeclampsia, chronic hypertension
Proteinuria Definition: Mild preclampsia: 1+ on dipstick or 300 mg/24 h urine, Severe preclampsia: >=5 g/24 h or 4+ on dipstick
Additional PE Criteria: Severe preeclampsia was defined as the presence of >=1 of the following: (1) high blood pressure, >=160/110 mm Hg on 2 occasions >=4 hours apart; (2) proteinuria, >=5 g/24 h or 4+ on dipstick; (3) thrombocytopenia, <100 000 platelets per milliliter; (4) oliguria, <400 mL/24 h; (5) pulmonary edema; or (6) elevated liver enzymes (SGOT/PT). A severe variant of preeclampsia called HELLP syndrome (hemolysis, elevated liver enzyme, low platelets) was defined by thrombocytopenia (<100 000 platelets per milliliter), SGOT/PT (>70), and hemolysis (as demonstrated by any of the following: total bilirubin >1.2 mg/dL, serum lactate dehydrogenase >=600 U/L, and hemolytic anemia on smear). Nulliparous preeclampsia was defined as preeclampsia in the first pregnancy progressing beyond 20 weeks. Multiparous preeclampsia was defined as the absence of preeclampsia in the first pregnancy beyond 20 weeks but preeclampsia diagnosed in a subsequent pregnancy.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Women were considered to have severe preeclampsia if they had either (1) an increase from baseline systolic blood pressure of at least 25 mm Hg and/ or an increase from baseline diastolic pressure of at least 15 mm Hg; or (2) the presence of systolic pressure of at least 140 mm Hg and/or the presence of diastolic pressure of at least 90 mm Hg. These levels had to occur on at least two occasions 6 hr apart or more. The level of proteinuria had to be >0.3 g/L in a 24-hr specimen, or the dipstick proteinuria score had to be >=2 in random urine collection. Women who met these criteria and experienced convulsions or unconsciousness in the prenatal period were classified as having eclampsia.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Women with preexisting hypertension or other medical conditions known to predispose them to preeclampsia were excluded.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Women with preexisting hypertension or other medical conditions known to predispose them to preeclampsia were excluded.
Proteinuria Definition: The level of proteinuria had to be >0.3 g/L in a 24-hr specimen, or the dipstick proteinuria score had to be >=2 in random urine collection

Preeclampsia was defined as the presence of hypertension associated with proteinuria after the 20th week of gestation in women known to be normotensive beforehand. Hypertension was defined as a blood pressure of at least 140 mm Hg (systolic) and/or 90 mm Hg (diastolic) on two occasions of up to 46 h apart. The blood pressure was measured on the right arm and with the patient always in the seated position. Proteinuria was defined as urinary excretion of 300 mg or more of protein in 24 h.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: no rise in blood pressure, no hypertension or proteinuria, similar age (+/- 2 years), no biological relationship and a delivery date as close as possible to the delivery date(s) of the patient group and with a follow up for at least 3 months after delivery. All women who had chronic hypertension, renal disease, diabetes, collagen vascular diseases, cancer or thrombosis were not included in the study.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: All women who had chronic hypertension, renal disease, diabetes, collagen vascular diseases, cancer or thrombosis were not included in the study.
Proteinuria Definition: urinary excretion of 300 mg or more of protein in 24 h

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Preeclampsia was defined by means of strict criteria: as a rise of blood pressure (>=30 mmHg systolic or >=15 mmHg diastolic over values in the first 20 weeks or, if blood pressure was unknown before 20 weeks gestation); late-pregnancy hypertension (defined as an absolute blood pressure >=140/90 mmHg); and proteinuria (>=2 + [1 g/l] on a voided specimen or >=1 + [0.3 g/l] on a catheterised specimen).
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Control subjects were selected according to the following criteria: first pregnancy, no rise in blood pressure, no hypertension or proteinuria, similar age (+/-5 years) and a delivery date as close as possible to the delivery date of the case subject. Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Preeclampsia was defined by increased blood pressure (>= 140 mm Hg systolic or >= 90 mm Hg diastolic on >= 2 occasions at least 6 h apart) that occurred after 20 weeks of gestation in a woman with previously normal blood pressure, accompanied by proteinuria (>= 0.3 g/24 h). Blood pressure returned to normal by 12 weeks postpartum in each preeclamptic study patient. Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Preeclampsia was defined as the development of hyperten- sion and proteinuria (>300 mg urinary protein in 24 h) in women with no baseline proteinuria. Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE/E was defined a priori using standard criteria including at least a semiquantitative measure of proteinuria.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: The control group consisted of women without a history of PE/E in pregnancy. Studies that used controls recruited from a general population (for example, blood donors) were included but sensitivity analyses without these studies were performed. Cases and controls were matched for ethnic group or the study reported the ethnic ancestry of participants to allow for stratified analysis.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Studies that included women with pre-existing or gestational hypertension without proteinuria were excluded.

Authors: de Lima TH et al. (Daher S)
PE Women Details: 92 with PE, 73 with eclampsia
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: All women with a single live pregnancy and who were referred to a single hospital (Santa Monica Obstetric Clinic) were eligible. The diagnoses of PE and E were based on the criteria of the Report of the National High Blood Pressure Education Program.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: All women with a single live pregnancy and who were referred to a single hospital (Santa Monica Obstetric Clinic) were eligible.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria were multiple gestation, fetal death, autoimmune disease, diabetes, uterine malformation, in vitro fertilization treatment, placental abruption, any infection, cancer or any other systemic disease, including preexisting hypertension.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Inclusion criteria were age >=18 years, Caucasian origin (defined as 4 grandparents born in Europe, or in the Maghreb), gestational age >=20 weeks, and PE defined according to the definition of the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG). PE was defined according to the ACOG as elevated blood pressure (>=140/90 mm Hg) occurring after 20 weeks of gestation with previously normal blood pressure, and proteinuria (>=0.3 g in a 24-hour urine specimen). PE was defined as early if gestational age at diagnosis was <34 weeks.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Controls were normotensive pregnant women; for each PE patient, a control matched for maternal age (+/-2 years), gestational term (+/-2 weeks) and ethnic origin (European or Maghrebian) was included. Controls who developed PE after enrolment were excluded from the study and replaced by another subject matched with the corresponding case.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Patients with proteinuria occurring before 20 gestational weeks were excluded.
Proteinuria Definition: >=0.3 g in a 24-hour urine specimen

Journal: European Journal of Obstetrics & Gynecology and Reproductive Biology
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE was defined as a blood pressure >140/90 mmHg after 20 weeks of gestation on two separated readings at least 6 h apart with proteinuria (>300 mg/L). PE women were primigravida and the gestational age during the sampling was 35 +/- 3 weeks.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: At least two live births and who experienced no adverse pregnancy outcome, volunteered as controls. Controls were not on oral contraceptives and were in the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle during sampling. Abortion and autoimmunity were considered as exclusion criteria for the control group. All women (both PE and controls) were not on any medication, were non-smokers and were free from cardiovascular, hepatic, renal, endocrine and metabolic disorders.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Women with previously diagnosed hypertension were excluded from the study. All women (both PE and controls) were not on any medication, were non-smokers and were free from cardiovascular, hepatic, renal, endocrine and metabolic disorders.

PE Women Details: PE group was divided into three subgroups: (1) mild (n = 47) and severe (n = 117) by disease severity, (2) term (n = 95) and preterm (n = 69) by gestational weeks at delivery, and (3) absence (n = 107) and presence of IUGR (n = 57) by fetal birth weight.
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE was defined as hypertension (systolic blood pressure >=140 mmHg and/or diastolic blood pressure >=90 mmHg) and proteinuria (>=300 mg in a 24-hr urine collection and/or >=1+ on dipstick testing) after 20 weeks of gestation, according to the Committee Terminology of the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists. Severe PE was defined as diastolic blood pressure >=110 mmHg; severe proteinuria (urinary protein excretion >=5 g per 24 hr and/or >=3 + on dipstick testing); evidence of pulmonary edema; seizures; oliguria (<500 mL/day); thrombocytopenia (platelet count <100 000/mL); and severe central nervous system symptoms such as altered mental status, headaches, blurred vision, or blindness.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria included major congenital anomalies; prior PE; taking drugs; alcohol consumption; smoking; and pre-existing medical conditions such as diabetes, chronic hypertension, autoimmune disease, or renal disease.
Proteinuria Definition: proteinuria (>=300 mg in a 24-hr urine collection and/or >=1+ on dipstick testing) severe proteinuria (urinary protein excretion >=5 g per 24 hr and/or >=3 + on dipstick testing)

Sample Type: blood sample, blood stain on filter paper, or oral swab sample
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Inclusion criteria: birth of a single live-born child in 1998 or 1999, the pregnancy or birth was registered in the Danish Hospital Discharge Register with a diagnosis of severe pre-eclampsia or eclampsia (ICD-10 codes O14.1 or O15), and for whom blood samples from the mother and the child were stored in the biobank. In Denmark, the diagnosis of severe pre-eclampsia requires a blood pressure >180/110 mmHg and/or the presence of severe subjective symptoms and/or proteinuria of >=5 g/l.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: For each of the case families, four potential controls were identified to be matched on the following criteria: same year and place of birth as the case child, same parity, and no diagnosis of hypertension, pre-eclampsia or eclampsia (ICD-10 codes O10-O16) registered in the Danish Hospital Discharge Register for the actual pregnancy or birth.
Proteinuria Definition: proteinuria of >=5 g/l

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE was defined as new onset of elevated blood pressure >=140/90mmHg using a standard mercury sphygmomanometer along with proteinuria >=2+ on dipstick on two occasions at least 6h apart or 4300mg per day on two occasions after 20 weeks of gestation in earlier normotensive pregnant women
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: The normotensive control group had women with uncomplicated gestation and blood pressure <125/85 mm Hg and no proteinuria.

PE Women Details: 88 Severe PE, 17 Mild PE
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Mild PE was defined as systolic blood pressure (SBP) >=140mmHg or diastolic blood pressure (DBP) >=90 mm Hg after 20 weeks of gestation on at least two occasions 6 or more hours apart. In addition, proteinuria was defined as 4300 mg per 24-h collection or persistent 1+ protein measurement on urine dipstick. The diagnosis of severe PE required the basic features of mild PE as well as some indication of additional problems with either the mother or the baby, including: (i) very high blood pressure (>160 mm Hg SBP or 110 mm Hg DBP) and (ii) proteinuria 45 g per 24-h collection. Only women with the aforementioned criteria within their first and not subsequent pregnancies were included in the study.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: The women with normal pregnancies were chosen as healthy controls based on comparable age, Han origin and geographical location. No family history of PE
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Subjects with a clinical history of primary liver and kidney disease, essential hypertension, diabetes mellitus, rheumatism, tumors and those who used drugs within the preceding 24 h were excluded from the study.
Proteinuria Definition: Mild PE: 4300 mg per 24-h collection or persistent 1+ protein measurement on urine dipstick; Severe PE: 45 g per 24-h collection

PE Women Details: Third Trimester
Control Women Details: Third Trimester
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Pregnancy-induced hypertension was defined as persistent (6 or more hours apart) blood pressure of at least 140/90 mmHg arising after 20 weeks of gestation. Preeclampsia was diagnosed when there was proteinuria in addi- tion to elevated blood pressure. Proteinuria was defined as urine protein concentration >300 mg/l or more (or 1+ on a urine dipstick) in at least two random specimens collected at least 4 hours apart in the absence of urinary tract infection.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: All women had a naturally conceived singleton pregnancy. Women with diabetes mellitus, gestational diabetes, chronic hypertension, renal disease, polycystic ovarian syndrome, hirsutism or menstrual cycle disturbances and women previously treated for infertility were excluded from the study.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Women with diabetes mellitus, gestational diabetes, chronic hypertension, renal disease, polycystic ovarian syndrome, hirsutism or menstrual cycle disturbances and women previously treated for infertility were excluded from the study.
Proteinuria Definition: Proteinuria was defined as urine protein concentration >300 mg/l or more (or 1+ on a urine dipstick) in at least two random specimens collected at least 4 hours apart in the absence of urinary tract infection.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: No previous history of hypertension, cardiovascular, or renal disease before pregnancy and blood pressure values exceeding 140/90 mmHg after the 20th week of gestation, confirmed by two consecutive readings at least six hours apart, with blood pressure reverting to normal within two months after delivery. The subjects were considered to have a physiological pregnancy if they did not have obstetrical, medical, or surgical complications of pregnancy, and delivered a term (>38 weeks) neonate with a birth weight above the 10th percentile for gestational age
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Subjects who had chronic hypertension of any etiology before pregnancy without superimposed consequent pre-eclampsia were not included in the study, as they might carry such genetic variants that are protective against pre-clampsia development.

Journal: Journal of Obstetrics and Gynaecology Research
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE was diagnosed from the presence of blood pressure 140/ 90 mm Hg and proteinuria 0.3 g in a 24-hour urine specimen or urine dipstick 1+ or more that occurred after 20 weeks of gestation. All patients with eclampsia, HELLP syndrome and other complications of PE were included.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Chronic hypertension and concomitant diabetes or renal and cardiovascular diseases were regarded as exclusion criteria for cases and controls.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Patients with hypertension diagnosed before 20 weeks and pre-existing chronic hypertension were excluded. Women with hypertension detected for the first time in pregnancy after 20 weeks or after delivery, but with no previous records, were also excluded. Women with gestational hypertension were also excluded as this entity may be of varied etiological origin. Chronic hypertension and concomitant diabetes or renal and cardiovascular diseases were regarded as exclusion criteria for cases and controls.

Sample Type: maternal blood, cord blood, and neonatal cheek swab
PE Women Details: 528 Chilean dyads, 424 Black women, 375 Black neonates
Control Women Details: 575 Chilean dyads, 412 Black women, 462 Neonates
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Preeclampsia was defined based on the presence of gestational hypertension (systolic blood pressure >=140 mmHg and/or diastolic blood pressure >=90 mmHg) and proteinuria (>=300 mg in a 24-hour urine collection, two or more dipstick measurement of 1+, or one or more dipstick measurement >=2+) according to ACOG[1] and the National High Blood Pressure Education Program
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Patients were considered to have a normal pregnancy outcome if they did not have any medical, obstetrical, or surgical complication, and delivered a term neonate (>=37 weeks) of appropriate birth weight for gestational age without complications.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria included: (1) known major fetal anomaly or demise; (2) multi-fetal pregnancy; (3) serious maternal medical illness (renal insufficiency, congestive heart disease, etc.); (4) refusal to provide written informed consent; and (5) a clinical emergency, which prevented counseling of the patient about participating in the study, such as fetal distress or maternal hemorrhage.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Women between 15-38 years old with singleton pregnancy, 16-38 gestation weeks (GW), who lived in the metropolitan area of Monterrey, were eligible to participate. Two recordings of diastolic blood pressure of 90 mmHg at least 4 h apart in previously normotensive women and proteinuria of 300 mg or more in 24 h, or two readings of at least ++ on dipstick analyses. PE was considered severe if blood pressure of 160 mm Hg systolic or higher or 110 mm Hg diastolic or higher on two occasions at least 6 hours apart while the patient was on bed rest, and proteinuria of 5 g or higher in a 24-hour urine specimen or 3+ or greater in two random urine samples collected at least 4 hours apart were present
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria included multiple pregnancies, pregnancies with structural or chromosomic fetus malformations detected by ultrasound, chronic hypertension, chronic renal disease, gestational diabetes mellitus, and underlying medical diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, and systemic lupus erythematosus.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria included multiple pregnancies, pregnancies with structural or chromosomic fetus malformations detected by ultrasound, chronic hypertension, chronic renal disease, gestational diabetes mellitus, and underlying medical diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, and systemic lupus erythematosus.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Preeclampsia was defined as a blood pressure of >=140/90 mmHg on two different occasions >4 h apart in previously normotensive women, associated with proteinuria in >300 mg/L in a 24-h collection in the absence of urinary tract infection.

Proteinuria Definition: >300 mg/L in a 24-h collection in the absence of urinary tract infection.

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Women were considered preeclamptic if they were previously normotensive and if they, on at least two occasions six or more hours apart, had after 20 weeks gestation (i) a rise in systolic blood pressure (SBP) of at least 25 mmHg and/or a rise from baseline diastolic blood pressure (DBP) of at least 15 mmHg, or (ii) SBP>=140 mmHg and/or DBP>=90 mmHg. Additionally, significant new onset proteinuric levels were either >=0.3 g/l in a 24 hour specimen, at least a 2+ proteinuria dipstick reading from a random urine collection or a spot protein:creatine ratio >=0.03 g/mmol. Preeclamptic women who also experienced convulsions or unconsciousness in their perinatal period were classified as having eclampsia.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Women with pre-existing hypertension or other medical conditions known to predispose for preeclampsia (e.g. renal disease, diabetes, twin pregnancies or fetal chromosomal abnormalities) were excluded.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Women with pre-existing hypertension or other medical conditions known to predispose for preeclampsia (e.g. renal disease, diabetes, twin pregnancies or fetal chromosomal abnormalities) were excluded.
Proteinuria Definition: either >=0.3 g/l in a 24 hour specimen, at least a 2+ proteinuria dipstick reading from a random urine collection or a spot protein:creatine ratio >=0.03 g/mmol.

Journal: Journal of Obstetrics and Gynaecology Research
Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Pre-eclampsia was defined as hypertension of >=140/90 mmHg on two occasions 6 hapart occurring after 20 weeks of gestation in a previously normotensive woman along with proteinuria of >1+ on the urine protein heat coagulation test (HCT, equivalent to 500 mg protein/day), which was not associated with urinary tract infection or ruptured membranes.
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: All control subjects had two or more living children and did not have a previous history of pregnancy loss.
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Exclusion criteria included: non-Sinhalese or women of mixed ethnicity, current pregnancy fathered by a non-Sinhalese man; renal disease, chronic hypertension, or persistent proteinuria (dened as >=1+ on the HCT in the first three urine samples tested in pregnancy with or without urinary tract infection); ischemic heart disease, cerebrovascular accidents, insulin- ornon-insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus; body mass index (BMI)  >=+30 kg/m2 based on height and weight measured at the antenatal booking visit, or postpartumin the case of unbooked pregnancies (to minimize phenotypic heterogeneity, as obesity itself is a risk factor for pre-eclampsia); a previous abortion after 12 weeks of gestation (because the uterus mimics a parous uterus due to uterine vascular re-modeling); and hydatidiform mole, multiple pregnancy, or gestational diabetes in the current pregnancy

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: PE was defined as hypertension with proteinuria occurring after the 20th week of gestation, but resolving by the 12th week postpartum. Subjects were diagnosed with hypertension if they had a systolic blood pressure (SBP) above 140 mmHg and/or a diastolic blood pressure (DBP) above 90 mmHg on repeated prelabor measurements. We ascertained that all PE and GH patients were normotensive before 20 weeks of gestation and that they also had blood pressures that returned to normal in the puerperium. The proteinuria criteria was greater than 1+ on a dipstick test, greater than 2+ protein on a voided urine sample, and greater than 300 mg on a 24 h urine specimen or a protein/creatinine ratio of 0.3. These criteria are compatible with the fundamental characteristics of HP established by the International Society of the Study of Hypertension in Pregnancy (ISSHP)

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: 2002 ACOG definitions (15): preeclampsia (new onset hypertension of at least 140 / 90 mmHg combined with proteinuria) in the presence of one of thefollowing: a systolic blood pressure t160 mmHg, diastolic blood pressure t110mmHg, severe proteinuria of 5g/24 h or >2+ on dipstick, severe headaches,thrombocytopenia (platelet count <100,000 per Pl), persistent epigastric /right upperquadrant pain or abnormal liver enzymes (aspartate aminotransferase ASAT t 100IU/l or LDH 1000 IU/l). Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Criteria for diagnosing PE/PIH have beendescribed before [14]. Persistent (6 or more hours apart) blood pressure of at least 140/90mmHg arising after 20 weeks of gestation was considered as PIH. Urine proteinconcentration >300 mg/l or more (or 1+ on a urine dipstick) in addition to hypertension wasconsidered as pre-eclampsia.
Proteinuria Definition: Urine proteinconcentration >300 mg/l or more (or 1+ on a urine dipstick)

Initial Inclusion Criteria for Cases (ha: Primiparas who had no indication of hypertension on their infants birth certificate. PE was defined according to National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute (NHLBI) guidelines ashaving de novo hypertension (systolic blood pressure >=140 mmHg or diastolic blood pressure>=90 mmHg on two or more occasions at least six hours apart after the 20th week of gestation)and accompanying proteinuria (urine protein concentration >=300 mg/L, equivalent to dipstickprotein test value of 1+ from two or more specimens collected at least four hours apart; oneor more urinary dipstick values of 2+ near the end of pregnancy; one or more catheterizeddipstick value of 1+ during delivery hospitalization; or a 24-hour urine collection with protein>300 mg).
Controls Inclusion/Exclusion Criteria: Potential controls were excluded if their medical records includedany indication of high blood pressure (systolic blood pressure >=140 mmHg or diastolic bloodpressure >=90 mmHg) in the prenatal or postpartum period, two or more high blood pressurereadings in the intrapartum period, or any indication of proteinuria during pregnancy (1+ ondipstick protein testing on two or more occasions).
PE Phenotype Exclusion Criteria: Potential cases were excluded if pre-existing hypertension could not be ruled out,only partial criteria for PE were met, or a definitive diagnosis could not be made due toincomplete information. Also excluded if age <18 years at delivery; non-English-speaking; history of an autoimmune disease (e.g. systemiclupus erythematosus, insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, rheumatoid arthritis); recurrentspontaneous abortion (>3 sequential pregnancy losses); chronic hypertension; pluralgestations; major congenital anomalies; infant death; or seriously ill infant.
Proteinuria Definition: Urine protein concentration >=300 mg/L, equivalent to dipstickprotein test value of 1+ from two or more specimens collected at least four hours apart; oneor more urinary dipstick values of 2+ near the end of pregnancy; one or more catheterizeddipstick value of 1+ during delivery hospitalization; or a 24-hour urine collection with protein>300 mg
